    <description>The Huygens Probe was part of the NASA/ESA Cassini-Huygens mission to study Saturn and its largest moon, Titan. The mission was launched in 1997 and Huygens Probe arrived on Titan in early 2005 after a controlled descent through Titanâ€™s atmosphere. The Huygens system comprised two main components: the 318 kg Probe and the 30 kg Probe Support Equipment (PSE) attached to the Cassini Orbiter. The Probe featured an Entry Assembly and a Descent Module containing scientific instruments and subsystems responsible for descent control, thermal management, and power distribution.
The Probe was the first spacecraft to land on Titan. It used parachutes to descend, which took about 2 hours and 27 minutes, during which time its instruments studied the atmosphere and weather. The Probe lasted roughly 1 hour and 10 minutes on the surface, where it took surface images, and studied several surface properties of Titan.
</description>
